Setting Up User Information
Set global username:
Example: git config --global user.name "JohnDoe"

Set global email:
Example: git config --global user.email "john@example.com"

Initializing and Cloning Repositories
Initialize an empty Git repository:
Example: git init my-project

Clone an existing Git repository:
Example: git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git

Staging and Committing Changes
Add a specific file:
Example: git add index.html

Add all files:
Example: git add .

Commit staged files:
Example: git commit -m "Initial commit"

Managing Modifications
Restore a modified file:
Example: git restore index.html or git checkout index.html
Checking Repository Status
Show the status of the repository:
Example: git status

Show branches in the repository:
Example: git branch

Branch Management
Checkout to a new branch:
Example: git checkout -b feature-branch

Checkout to an existing branch:
Example: git checkout main

Remove a branch:
Example: git branch -d old-branch

Remote Repository Management
Show remote origin URL:
Example: git remote -v

Add remote origin URL:
Example: git remote add origin https://github.com/user/repo.git

Remove remote origin URL:
Example: git remote remove origin

Syncing with Remote Repositories
Fetch all remote branches:
Example: git fetch

Push local changes to a remote branch:
Example: git push origin main

Pull remote changes to local branch:
Example: git pull origin main

Viewing Commits and Logs
Check commits and logs:
Example: git log
